   =20
      Volcano bonds
   =20
 =20
I don=E2=80=99t give investing advice around here, but the other day I did =
 have some nice things to say about the El Salvador 8.25% bond due in 2032.=
 Relatively nice things, anyway. Last week El Salvador announced that it wa=
s issuing a $1 billion =E2=80=9Cvolcano bond,=E2=80=9D a 6.5% bond due in 2=
032 that will be issued on a blockchain, will be pitched to crypto fans, an=
d will come with a call option on $250 million of Bitcoin. I said, well, in=
stead of buying that, you can buy the 8.25% bond for about 75 cents on the =
dollar and put the other 25 cents into buying Bitcoin. That way you get a h=
igher yield (8.25% is more than 6.5%) and more Bitcoin exposure ($25 worth =
of Bitcoin is a bit more Bitcoin than an at-the-money call option on $25 of=
 Bitcoin).=C2=A0How is that working out? I really must emphasize that nothi=
ng here is ever investing advice; here=E2=80=99s  a Bloomberg article from =
Friday:Dollar bonds from El Salvador are among the worst-performing in emer=
ging markets so far this month, lagging only defaulted Lebanese debt, accor=
ding to data compiled from a Bloomberg index.=C2=A0The selloff in the bonds=
 came as investors weighed the possibility of higher indebtedness in the Ce=
ntral American nation, as well as rising concern it will not reach a deal w=
ith the International Monetary Fund.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CBitcoin Bond Plan Sends =
El Salvador=E2=80=99s Dollar Debt Diving,=E2=80=9D says  this Bloomberg hea=
dline from early last week. And those 8.25% bonds now seem to trade at abou=
t 68 cents on the dollar, down about 10% from when we last discussed them. =
Oh well.In some vague financial theory, if El Salvador succeeds in issuing =
these volcano bonds, somebody should (1) buy the 8.25% bonds and some Bitco=
in along the lines I proposed, (2) short the volcano bonds and (3) collect =
a risk-free profit. Arguably this should be=C2=A0good=C2=A0for the price of=
 El Salvador=E2=80=99s existing debt.But in practice it seems very hard to =
actually do the arbitrage here.=C2=A0The only people realistically buying E=
l Salvador=E2=80=99s 8.25% bonds are, like, grizzled emerging-markets veter=
ans. Those bonds do not trade in particularly convenient ways; the average =
retail speculator is not going to go buy them. Those grizzled veterans migh=
t or might not be able to buy Bitcoin to complete the long side of the arbi=
trage; if you run an emerging-market fund it is not obvious that your manda=
te would allow buying Bitcoin. Meanwhile I do not know a lot about the bloc=
kchain apparatus that will be used to issue the volcano bonds, but I am goi=
ng to guess that (1) neither do those emerging-markets veterans and (2) it =
probably will not make it=C2=A0easy=C2=A0to short the volcano bonds.=C2=A0S=
o doing the arbitrage involves trading three markets =E2=80=94=C2=A0EM bond=
s, Bitcoin, and short selling on the volcano bond=E2=80=99s blockchain plat=
form =E2=80=94=C2=A0that do not have a lot of overlap.=C2=A0Meanwhile the p=
eople buying El Salvador=E2=80=99s 6.5% Bitcoin bonds will be, like, crypto=
 fans who enjoy going to crypto parties with El Salvador=E2=80=99s crypto-b=
ro president.=C2=A0They=C2=A0are not going to go figure out how to buy the =
8.25% bond to get better economics than the volcano bond; that requires usi=
ng antiquated traditional-finance infrastructure and won=E2=80=99t get them=
 invited to the parties. I suspect that El Salvador=E2=80=99s efforts at ma=
rket segmentation will just work; there is no reason for the price of its v=
olcano bonds to track the price of its regular bonds, and they probably won=
=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0
