      Everything is securities fraud
   =20
 =20
Is it securities fraud to refuse to sell ice cream in the occupied Palestin=
ian territories? Folks, everything is securities fraud:A Bronx congressman =
is asking the Securities and Exchange Commission to demand the parent compa=
ny of Ben & Jerrys to amend their regulatory filings to reflect potential n=
ew risks caused by the woke ice cream maker=E2=80=99s decision to no longer=
 peddle its products in parts of Israel.Participating in the Boycott Divest=
ment and Sanctions movement against Israel can result in potentially stiff =
financial consequences in more than 30 states =E2=80=94 including New York,=
 which has moved to divest more than $100 million in pension funds from Uni=
lever.=E2=80=9CUnilever is a widely held company with a current market capi=
talization of $135 billion, which places in jeopardy the manifold United St=
ates institutions, pension funds, and endowments which hold its shares on b=
ehalf of its beneficiaries,=E2=80=9D reads the letter sent to SEC Chairman =
Gary Gensler on Friday.=E2=80=9CWe believe that these actions require the S=
EC to request that the regulatory filings of Unilever be amended to disclos=
e the material risk factors.=E2=80=9DOf all the ways that the world=E2=80=
=99s leading superpower can conduct foreign policy, =E2=80=9Casking a Briti=
sh consumer company to update its U.S. securities filings to=C2=A0add risk =
factors about=C2=A0its=C2=A0premium-ice-cream subsidiary=E2=80=9D is =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0a weird one? Just, like, there you are in Congress, you have some =
foreign policy issue that you want to do something about, and the most natu=
ral thing to do about it is to send a letter to the SEC. Because U.S. forei=
gn policy, like so much of U.S. policy, is a subset of securities law.
