      NFT Stuff (1)
   =20
 =20
Here is a=C2=A0story about Lucian Freud, the major modern painter, who appa=
rently denied that he painted some of his paintings because he was mad at t=
heir owners:Almost 25 years ago, a Swiss art collector bought a Lucian Freu=
d painting =E2=80=93 a full-length male nude =E2=80=93 at auction. He then =
received a call from the British artist, asking to buy it from him. The two=
 men did not know each other, and the collector politely refused, as he lik=
ed the picture.Three days later, he claims he received another call from a =
now furious Freud who told him that, unless he sold it to him, he would den=
y having painted it.The collector, who wishes to remain anonymous, told the=
 Observer: =E2=80=9CHe said: =E2=80=98I=E2=80=99ll give you more than you p=
aid, I=E2=80=99ll double it.=E2=80=99 I declined, and he became very aggres=
sive, with bad words. He said: =E2=80=98In that case, you will never sell i=
t.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D To his dismay, the Freud estate subsequently refused t=
o authenticate Standing Male Nude =E2=80=93 and that could have been the en=
d of a sad tale for the collector. =E2=80=A6In 2016, an early Freud picture=
 was attributed to the artist, despite his own denials that he painted it. =
Philip Mould=E2=80=99s BBC show Fake or Fortune? uncovered evidence that in=
cluded notes from the artist=E2=80=99s former solicitor. The artist had app=
arently refused to acknowledge the work because it was originally owned by =
Denis Wirth-Miller, an artist with whom Freud had a long-running feud.So, o=
ne, on a personal level, that=E2=80=99s great: The man devoted his life to =
art, but he never let his commitment to that art get in the way of his pett=
y personal feuds. Truly something to aspire to.Two, in each case these pain=
tings were authenticated over Freud=E2=80=99s objection through some combin=
ation of extrinsic documentary evidence, pigment analysis and connoisseursh=
ip. (Also, like, artificial-intelligence connoisseurship? =E2=80=9COur AI h=
as classified parts of the painting as being by the hand of Freud with a hi=
gh score =E2=80=93 a positive result up to 95%,=E2=80=9D says someone.) Tha=
t=E2=80=99s cool for the owners. Would you rather own a genuine Freud that =
he acknowledged, or one that he denied? I feel like the ones he denied are =
rarer and more interesting? They=E2=80=99ve got more of a story to them, th=
ey=E2=80=99re more fun, I bet they=E2=80=99re more valuable. If you owned a=
 genuine Freud and were friends with him, would it have been a good idea to=
 ask him to deny the painting (and give you a note saying =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=
=99m going to deny that I painted this out of pique=E2=80=9D) to make it mo=
re valuable?Three, blah blah blah put the paintings on the blockchain as no=
n-fungible tokens blah blah blah then this would never happen blah blah bla=
h. Actually I feel like you could have some fun with that? You=E2=80=99ve g=
ot three sort-of-incommensurable things: the (living, human) painter (not F=
reud =E2=80=94=C2=A0he died before NFTs were invented =E2=80=94=C2=A0but so=
meone else could do this), the (physical) painting, and some digital object=
 on some blockchain signed with some public key. =E2=80=9CThis digital obje=
ct was verifiably issued by this crypto wallet,=E2=80=9D you can say pretty=
 definitively, but the painter can sit around saying =E2=80=9Cah yes but th=
at=E2=80=99s not the painting that corresponds to the digital object=E2=80=
=9D or =E2=80=9Cah yes but that crypto wallet is not mine=E2=80=9D or, why =
not, both. I feel like there are rich veins of NFT prank that haven=E2=80=
=99t really been mined yet.
