10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">SPARCman</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How much would you pay for the right t=
o buy one share of one big future=C2=A0initial public offering at the IPO p=
rice? What a strange question. You don=E2=80=99t know which IPO it will be,=
 or when, or what the price is. Just some big company, sometime in the futu=
re. One useful piece of information is that most IPOs go up; in particular,=
 the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25866447.2706=
56/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmFzZGFxLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy90cmVuZHMtaW4taXBvLXBvcHMtMjAy=
MS0wMy0wNA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb1d3f176" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">average first-day IPO=
 pop</a> is around 18%. So if you buy a share at the IPO price and sell imm=
ediately, you=E2=80=99ll probably make about 18%, though there is a lot of =
variance around that number.[1] But let=E2=80=99s just say=C2=A0you=E2=80=
=99ll make 18% =E2=80=94=C2=A0but 18% of what? If the IPO price is $10, you=
=E2=80=99ll make $1.80, and the right to buy one share is worth about $1.80=
 discounted for time (I also haven=E2=80=99t told you when this IPO will ha=
ppen) and general uncertainty. If the IPO price is $100, you=E2=80=99ll mak=
e $18, and the right to buy one share is worth about $18.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">It is a strange problem in option valuation. But the value c=
an=E2=80=99t be zero, can it? Most IPOs do go up; mostly shares price in a =
range of, you know, $10 to $100 or whatever. Being able to buy a share at t=
he IPO price is valuable. You=E2=80=99d pay something for it.=C2=A0I suppos=
e you put together your best guess at a probability distribution for when t=
his IPO will happen, how big it will be, and how much it will pop on its fi=
rst day, and you use that to estimate what the right is worth.=C2=A0</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s the first <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25866447.270656/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi=
9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4OTU1ODIvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIxMzQwNjAyL2QxNzU5MjBkc=
zEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0e1e89f7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">filing for Pershing Squa=
re SPARC Holdings Ltd.</a>, Bill Ackman=E2=80=99s next-generation SPAC. A S=
PAC is a special purpose acquisition company: It raises a pool of money fro=
m investors, puts the money in trust, looks for a private company to take p=
ublic, merges with the target company,=C2=A0gives it the cash and gives its=
 investors shares in the newly public target company. A SPARC is a special =
purpose acquisition=C2=A0<em>rights=C2=A0</em>company: It's like a SPAC, bu=
t instead of selling shares to investors for $10 each, it gives away =E2=80=
=9Cspecial purpose acquisition rights=E2=80=9D (SPARs) to investors for $0 =
each, and then when it finds a target company it asks the investors to put =
up some money to merge with the target. Before it finds a target, the SPARC=
 rights =E2=80=94=C2=A0which the SPARC gave away for free =E2=80=94=C2=A0tr=
ade on the stock exchange for whatever they=E2=80=99re worth, or I guess fo=
r whatever people think they=E2=80=99re worth. A somewhat mysterious number=
. Basically: How big a deal do you think Ackman will do, how fast will he d=
o it, and how good a deal will it be?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We ha=
ve <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25866447.270656=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDQvYm=
lsbC1hY2ttYW4tcy1zcGFjLXdpbGwtYmUtdGhyZWUtc3BhY3M_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEyOTIxX01PT=
kVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09=
MjExMTI5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB96659e60"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;"> talked</a> about Ackman=E2=80=99s SPARC idea <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25866447.270656/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb2=
1iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDcvc3BhY3MtY2FuLXNob290LW91d=
C1zcGFyY3M_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEyOTIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1f=
c291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMTI5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZ=
m/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6ca892fa" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> before</a> and I just find it=
 delightful? One fun thing about the SPARC is that, since it doesn=E2=80=99=
t raise the money in advance, there=E2=80=99s no real reason for it to be f=
or a fixed amount of money. Ackman will go find a target company, and he=E2=
=80=99ll figure out how much money the target company wants to raise, and t=
hen he=E2=80=99ll go to the SPARC investors and ask them for the money:</p>=
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SPARs will each be exercisable=
 for one Public Share, at a minimum exercise price of $10.00 per share. In =
connection with a proposed business combination, we may decide to seek a gr=
eater amount of capital from public investors, in which case we may increas=
e, but not decrease, the exercise price of our SPARs. If we decide to incre=
ase the exercise price of our SPARs, we will publicly announce such increas=
e at the time we announce that we have entered into a definitive agreement =
with respect to our business combination (the =E2=80=9CDefinitive Agreement=
=E2=80=9D). We refer to the $10.00 SPAR exercise price as the =E2=80=9CMini=
mum Exercise Price=E2=80=9D and to the publicly announced final exercise pr=
ice as the =E2=80=9CFinal Exercise Price.=E2=80=9D The total proceeds from =
the exercise of all SPARs at the Minimum Exercise Price will be $2,444,444,=
440. There is no maximum Final Exercise Price, and accordingly, no maximum =
amount of total proceeds we could raise from the exercise of all SPARs at t=
he Final Exercise Price (the =E2=80=9CFinal Exercise Proceeds=E2=80=9D). Fo=
r example, if we decided to raise twice as much public capital, each SPAR w=
ould become exercisable for one Public Share at a Final Exercise Price of $=
20.00, and the Final SPAR Proceeds would be $4,888,888,880.</p></blockquote=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also,=C2=A0Pershing Square Capital Management=
=C2=A0hedge funds will buy anywhere from $500 million to $3.5 billion of ta=
rget-company stock alongside the SPARC, meaning that the SPARC deal will be=
 for at least $2.9 billion but could be any arbitrary larger number.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another fun thing about the SPARC is that, since =
it doesn=E2=80=99t raise the money in advance, it=C2=A0just gives away its =
rights for free. In the case of Pershing Square=E2=80=99s SPARC, it plans t=
o give away the rights to shareholders of Pershing Square=E2=80=99s <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25866447.270656/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMjAvYmlsbC1hY2tt=
YW4tcy10aHJlZS1zcGFjcy13ZXJlLXRvby1tYW55P2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMjkyMV9NT05FWVNUVUZ=
GJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIxMTEyOS=
Z1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8717cea7" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
> somewhat abortive=C2=A0<em>SPAC</em></a>, Pershing Square Tontine Holding=
s. Then the SPARC would do a deal, raise money from SPARC rights holders, g=
ive them shares of the target company, and=C2=A0<em>also=C2=A0</em>give the=
m shares of a=C2=A0<em>new=C2=A0</em>SPARC that would go looking for anothe=
r deal, a sort of chain-SPARC business where each SPARC would, uh, spark th=
e next SPARC.[2] This adds to the fun of valuation. Let=E2=80=99s say you t=
hink each SPARC right is worth $3: You think that Ackman will announce a de=
al at about $10 to $20 a share and it will trade up by 15% to 30%; you aver=
age that out to $3 per share. But then when he announces the deal you get a=
nother SPARC right, which is also (let=E2=80=99s say) worth $3 per share. S=
o was your original SPARC right worth $6? But this continues indefinitely =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0the second SPARC deal comes with a third SPARC right,=C2=A0e=
tc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0so in theory you=E2=80=99re getting an indefinite string=
 of IPO pops, not just one. How much is that worth?</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">Also=C2=A0I suppose anyone could copy this structure and give the =
rights to whoever they want? It helps to have name recognition and an exist=
ing SPAC, as Ackman does, but if this structure catches on you could imagin=
e other people just air-dropping=C2=A0SPARCs onto some list of investors an=
d hoping that they trade.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The pitch to the =
target company is also very fun. I once <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/25866447.270656/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDQvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4tcy1zcGFjLXdpbGwtYmUtdGhy=
ZWUtc3BhY3M_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTEyOTIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1=
fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMTI5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dW=
Zm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC96659e60" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> wrote about it</a>:</p><bloc=
kquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bill Ackman can go around to private co=
mpanies looking to go public and say =E2=80=A6 what? =E2=80=9CHey, I=E2=80=
=99ve got some friends, and they are following with interest my efforts to =
find a company to merge with. If I find a good one, maybe they=E2=80=99ll g=
ive me money, though they haven=E2=80=99t given me any money yet and they=
=E2=80=99re under no obligation to do so. Would you like to be that company=
, and maybe my friends will give you their money? We can find out together!=
=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a company=
 looking to go public, is that pitch appealing? Kind of, right? You will be=
 comparing it to the pitch you are receiving from investment bankers to do =
a traditional initial public offering.[3] The investment bankers will want =
to charge you an underwriting fee of, say, 1% to 5% of the money you raise;=
 the SPARC has no underwriting fee. (It does require you to give=C2=A0Persh=
ing Square=C2=A0warrants to buy about 5% of your company, at a 20% premium =
to the IPO price, which is pretty significant, but you=E2=80=99re selling s=
tock at the IPO price anyway so perhaps you do not ascribe much value to th=
is.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The investment bankers will put togeth=
er a roadshow with a plan to pitch big investors on the merits of your comp=
any. Ackman will also do some of that; presumably when you announce the dea=
l he=E2=80=99ll do an investor presentation on the merits. But whereas the =
bankers will be starting from scratch =E2=80=94=C2=A0calling up big investo=
rs to say =E2=80=9CI have a cool company to tell you about=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0Ackman will already have done a lot of the work of fundraising. Th=
e SPARC rights will already trade publicly; they will already be held by an=
 audience of Ackman fans hoping to get in on his next deal. And their price=
 will react to the deal and give you a quick indication of whether it works=
: If you announce a deal with the SPARC and the rights trade up to $3, that=
 means that people will probably exercise their rights and that you=E2=80=
=99ll get your money; if you announce the deal and the rights trade down to=
 $0.01, that means they won=E2=80=99t and you should rethink the deal. Gett=
ing instant feedback on whether your IPO will work is sort of cool.=C2=A0</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A few other technical things. First, when th=
e SPARC announces a deal, the deal will in an important=C2=A0legal sense be=
 an initial public offering. (The SPARC will be=C2=A0asking investors for m=
oney, rather than, like a SPAC, offering to give them their money back.)=C2=
=A0This is=C2=A0<em>different=C2=A0</em>from a SPAC. With a SPAC, the SPAC =
does an IPO for cash and then trades publicly; when it announces a deal, th=
at=C2=A0is just a merger of a private company (the target) with a public co=
mpany (the SPAC). This means that the disclosure rules for SPAC mergers are=
 different from those for IPOs, and in particular, <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25866447.270656/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMTIvbWF5YmUtc3BhY3MtYXJlLXJlYWxse=
S1pcG9zP2NtcGlkPUJCRDExMjkyMV9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3Nv=
dXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIxMTEyOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3c309ce3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> it is generally assumed</a> tha=
t SPACs can market themselves based on projections of future revenue rather=
 than sticking to historical financial data. With a SPARC merger, the discl=
osure rules are the same as for any other IPO; the SPARC deal probably can=
=E2=80=99t be marketed based on overly optimistic projections.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second, for this to work, the New York Stock Exchange =
needs to change its listing rules to allow the listing of SPARC warrants. N=
YSE wants to do this =E2=80=94=C2=A0here is its <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/25866447.270656/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnlzZS5jb20vc=
HVibGljZG9jcy9ueXNlL21hcmtldHMvbnlzZS9ydWxlLWZpbGluZ3MvZmlsaW5ncy8yMDIxL1NS=
LU5ZU0UtMjAyMS00NSUyMFBERi5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa6d9b927" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
proposed rule change</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is not totally clear th=
at the Securities and Exchange Commission will allow it.[4] My basic model =
of the SEC and SPACs right now is that the SEC really doesn=E2=80=99t like =
SPACs. I don=E2=80=99t know which way this cuts. On the one hand, the SPARC=
 is SPAC-ish, and if the SEC hates everything SPAC-related it will not be i=
nterested in approving new SPAC-ish things. Also the valuation of SPARC rig=
hts does seem like a difficult puzzle, and a weird one for retail investors=
 to figure out. On the other hand, the SPARC solves some of the problems th=
e SEC has with SPACs (<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/25866447.270656/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGV=
